window.__XF_SKILL_PACKS__=window.__XF_SKILL_PACKS__||{};window.__XF_SKILL_PACKS__["meta-tools-pack"]={"id": "meta-tools-pack", "skills": [{"id": "code-review", "aiInstallPrompt": "Install the skill 'code-review' by writing the file below.\n\nUniversal path: ./skills/code-review/SKILL.md\nGrok path: ~/.grok/skills/code-review/SKILL.md\nCursor path: ~/.cursor/skills/code-review/SKILL.md\nClaude path: ~/.claude/skills/code-review/SKILL.md\nVS Code agent path: .github/skills/code-review/SKILL.md\n\nCreate the folder if needed, then write SKILL.md with this exact content:\n\n```markdown\n---\nname: code-review\ndescription: Run an extremely strict maintainability review for abstraction quality, giant files, and spaghetti-condition growth. Use for a deep code quality audit or an especially harsh maintainability review.\ndisable-model-invocation: true\n---\n\n# Strict Code Quality Review\n\nUse this skill for an unusually strict review focused on implementation quality, maintainability, abstraction quality, and codebase health.\n\nAbove all, this skill should push the reviewer to be **ambitious** about code structure. Do not merely identify local cleanup opportunities. Actively search for \"code judo\" moves: restructurings that preserve behavior while making the implementation dramatically simpler, smaller, more direct, and more elegant.\n\n## Works with\n\nUse this as a portable `SKILL.md` in Grok, Claude, Cursor, ChatGPT, Codex, VS Code agent skills, Gemini, or any AI workspace that supports reusable markdown instructions. If a tool does not support slash commands, paste the task and ask the AI to follow this skill.\n\n## Core Prompt\n\nStart from this baseline:\n\n> Perform a deep code quality audit of the current branch's changes.\n> Rethink how to structure / implement the changes to meaningfully improve code quality without impacting behavior.\n> Work to improve abstractions, modularity, reduce Spaghetti code, improve succinctness and legibility.\n> Be ambitious, if there is a clear path to improving the implementation that involves restructuring some of the codebase, go for it.\n> Be extremely thorough and rigorous. Measure twice, cut once.\n\n## Non-Negotiable Additional Standards\n\nApply the baseline prompt above, plus these explicit review rules:\n\n0. **Be ambitious about structural simplification.**\n   - Do not stop at \"this could be a bit cleaner.\"\n   - Look for opportunities to reframe the change so that whole branches, helpers, modes, conditionals, or layers disappear entirely.\n   - Prefer the solution that makes the code feel inevitable in hindsight.\n   - Assume there is often a \"code judo\" move available: a re-organization that uses the existing architecture more effectively and makes the change dramatically simpler and more elegant.\n   - If you see a path to delete complexity rather than rearrange it, push hard for that path.\n\n1. **Do not let a PR push a file from under 1k lines to over 1k lines without a very strong reason.**\n   - Treat this as a strong code-quality smell by default.\n   - Prefer extracting helpers, subcomponents, modules, or local abstractions instead of letting a file sprawl past 1000 lines.\n   - If the diff crosses that threshold, explicitly ask whether the code should be decomposed first.\n   - Only waive this if there is a compelling structural reason and the resulting file is still clearly organized.\n\n2. **Do not allow random spaghetti growth in existing code.**\n   - Be highly suspicious of new ad-hoc conditionals, scattered special cases, or one-off branches inserted into unrelated flows.\n   - If a change adds \"weird if statements in random places\", treat that as a design problem, not a stylistic nit.\n   - Prefer pushing the logic into a dedicated abstraction, helper, state machine, policy object, or separate module instead of tangling an existing path.\n   - Call out changes that make the surrounding code harder to reason about, even if they technically work.\n\n3. **Bias toward cleaning the design, not just accepting working code.**\n   - If behavior can stay the same while the structure becomes meaningfully cleaner, push for the cleaner version.\n   - Do not rubber-stamp \"it works\" implementations that leave the codebase messier.\n   - Strongly prefer simplifications that remove moving pieces altogether over refactors that merely spread the same complexity around.\n\n4. **Prefer direct, boring, maintainable code over hacky or magical code.**\n   - Treat brittle, ad-hoc, or \"magic\" behavior as a code-quality problem.\n   - Be skeptical of generic mechanisms that hide simple data-shape assumptions.\n   - Flag thin abstractions, identity wrappers, or pass-through helpers that add indirection without buying clarity.\n\n5. **Push hard on type and boundary cleanliness when they affect maintainability.**\n   - Question unnecessary optionality, `unknown`, `any`, or cast-heavy code when a clearer type boundary could exist.\n   - Prefer explicit typed models or shared contracts over loosely-shaped ad-hoc objects.\n   - If a branch relies on silent fallback to paper over an unclear invariant, ask whether the boundary should be made explicit instead.\n\n6. **Keep logic in the canonical layer and reuse existing helpers.**\n   - Call out feature logic leaking into shared paths or implementation details leaking through APIs.\n   - Prefer existing canonical utilities/helpers over bespoke one-offs.\n   - Push code toward the right package, service, or module instead of normalizing architectural drift.\n\n7. **Treat unnecessary sequential orchestration and non-atomic updates as design smells when the cleaner structure is obvious.**\n   - If independent work is serialized for no good reason, ask whether the flow should run in parallel instead.\n   - If related updates can leave state half-applied, push for a more atomic structure.\n   - Do not over-index on micro-optimizations, but do flag avoidable orchestration complexity that makes the implementation more brittle.\n\n## Primary Review Questions\n\nFor every meaningful change, ask:\n\n- Is there a \"code judo\" move that would make this dramatically simpler?\n- Can this change be reframed so fewer concepts, branches, or helper layers are needed?\n- Does this improve or worsen the local architecture?\n- Did the diff add branching complexity where a better abstraction should exist?\n- Did a previously cohesive module become more coupled, more stateful, or harder to scan?\n- Is this logic living in the right file and layer?\n- Did this change enlarge a file or component past a healthy size boundary?\n- Are there repeated conditionals that signal a missing model or missing helper?\n- Is the implementation direct and legible, or does it rely on special cases and incidental control flow?\n- Is this abstraction actually earning its keep, or is it just a wrapper?\n- Did the diff introduce casts, optionality, or ad-hoc object shapes that obscure the real invariant?\n- Is this logic living in the canonical layer, or did the diff leak details across a boundary?\n- Is this orchestration more sequential or less atomic than it needs to be?\n\n## What to Flag Aggressively\n\nEscalate findings when you see:\n\n- A complicated implementation where a cleaner reframing could delete whole categories of complexity.\n- Refactors that move code around but fail to reduce the number of concepts a reader must hold in their head.\n- A file crossing 1000 lines due to the PR, especially if the new code could be split out.\n- New conditionals bolted onto unrelated code paths.\n- One-off booleans, nullable modes, or flags that complicate existing control flow.\n- Feature-specific logic leaking into general-purpose modules.\n- Generic \"magic\" handling that hides simple structure and makes the code harder to reason about.\n- Thin wrappers or identity abstractions that add indirection without simplifying anything.\n- Unnecessary casts, `any`, `unknown`, or optional params that muddy the real contract.\n- Copy-pasted logic instead of extracted helpers.\n- Narrow edge-case handling implemented in the middle of an already busy function.\n- Refactors that technically pass tests but make the code less modular or less readable.\n- \"Temporary\" branching that is likely to become permanent debt.\n- Bespoke helpers where the codebase already has a canonical utility for the job.\n- Logic added in the wrong layer/package when it should live somewhere more central.\n- Sequential async flow where obviously independent work could stay simpler and clearer with parallel execution.\n- Partial-update logic that leaves state less atomic than necessary.\n\n## Preferred Remedies\n\nWhen you identify a code-quality problem, prefer suggestions like:\n\n- Delete a whole layer of indirection rather than polishing it.\n- Reframe the state model so conditionals disappear instead of getting centralized.\n- Change the ownership boundary so the feature becomes a natural extension of an existing abstraction.\n- Turn special-case logic into a simpler default flow with fewer exceptions.\n- Extract a helper or pure function.\n- Split a large file into smaller focused modules.\n- Move feature-specific logic behind a dedicated abstraction.\n- Replace condition chains with a typed model or explicit dispatcher.\n- Separate orchestration from business logic.\n- Collapse duplicate branches into a single clearer flow.\n- Delete wrappers that do not meaningfully clarify the API.\n- Reuse the existing canonical helper instead of introducing a near-duplicate.\n- Make type boundaries more explicit so the control flow gets simpler.\n- Move the logic to the package/module/layer that already owns the concept.\n- Parallelize independent work when that also simplifies the orchestration.\n- Restructure related updates into a more atomic flow when partial state would be harder to reason about.\n\nDo not be satisfied with \"maybe rename this\" feedback when the real issue is structural.\nDo not be satisfied with a merely cleaner version of the same messy idea if there is a plausible path to a much simpler idea.\n\n## Review Tone\n\nBe direct, serious, and demanding about quality.\nDo not be rude, but do not soften major maintainability issues into mild suggestions.\nIf the code is making the codebase messier, say so clearly.\nIf the implementation missed an opportunity for a dramatic simplification, say that clearly too.\n\nGood phrases:\n\n- `this pushes the file past 1k lines. can we decompose this first?`\n- `this adds another special-case branch into an already busy flow. can we move this behind its own abstraction?`\n- `this works, but it makes the surrounding code more spaghetti. let's keep the behavior and restructure the implementation.`\n- `this feels like feature logic leaking into a shared path. can we isolate it?`\n- `this abstraction seems unnecessary. can we just keep the direct flow?`\n- `why does this need a cast / optional here? can we make the boundary more explicit instead?`\n- `this looks like a bespoke helper for something we already have elsewhere. can we reuse the canonical one?`\n- `i think there's a code-judo move here that makes this much simpler. can we reframe this so these branches disappear?`\n- `this refactor moves complexity around, but doesn't really delete it. is there a way to make the model itself simpler?`\n\n## Output Expectations\n\nPrioritize findings in this order:\n\n1. Structural code-quality regressions\n2. Missed opportunities for dramatic simplification / code-judo restructuring\n3. Spaghetti / branching complexity increases\n4. Boundary / abstraction / type-contract problems that make the code harder to reason about\n5. File-size and decomposition concerns\n6. Modularity and abstraction issues\n7. Legibility and maintainability concerns\n\nDo not flood the review with low-value nits if there are larger structural issues.\nPrefer a smaller number of high-conviction comments over a long list of cosmetic notes.\n\n## Approval Bar\n\nDo not approve merely because behavior seems correct.\nThe bar for approval is:\n\n- no clear structural regression\n- no obvious missed opportunity to make the implementation dramatically simpler when such a path is visible\n- no unjustified file-size explosion\n- no obvious spaghetti-growth from special-case branching\n- no obviously hacky or magical abstraction that makes the code harder to reason about\n- no unnecessary wrapper/cast/optionality churn obscuring the real design\n- no clear architecture-boundary leak or avoidable canonical-helper duplication\n- no missed opportunity for an obvious decomposition that would materially improve maintainability\n\nTreat these as presumptive blockers unless the author can justify them clearly:\n\n- the PR preserves a lot of incidental complexity when there is a plausible code-judo move that would delete it\n- the PR pushes a file from below 1000 lines to above 1000 lines\n- the PR adds ad-hoc branching that makes an existing flow more tangled\n- the PR solves a local problem by scattering feature checks across shared code\n- the PR adds an unnecessary abstraction, wrapper, or cast-heavy contract that makes the design more indirect\n- the PR duplicates an existing helper or puts logic in the wrong layer when there is a clear canonical home\n\nIf those conditions are not met, leave explicit, actionable feedback and push for a cleaner decomposition.\n\n## When to use\n\nUse this when the user needs Run an extremely strict maintainability review for abstraction quality, giant files, and spaghetti-condition growth. Use for a deep code quality audit or an especially harsh maintainability review.\n\n## Inputs to gather\n\n- Files, diff, branch, or code context to review\n- The user's risk tolerance and desired review depth\n- Any known constraints, deadlines, or areas of concern\n\n## Workflow\n\n1. Inspect the relevant code before forming conclusions.\n2. Prioritize correctness, maintainability, safety, and missing tests.\n3. Lead with findings ordered by severity and cite file/line references when available.\n4. Separate confirmed issues from suggestions and open questions.\n\n## Output format\n\n**Findings**\n\n**Open questions**\n\n**Change summary**\n\n**Test gaps / residual risk**\n\n## Quality check (before responding)\n\n- [ ] Findings are grounded in code evidence\n- [ ] The most severe issue appears first\n- [ ] Suggestions do not require behavior changes unless clearly justified\n- [ ] The user can act on every listed item\n```\n\nAfter writing the file, confirm it exists. The user can then run /code-review or describe the task from the skill description.", "skillContent": "---\nname: code-review\ndescription: Run an extremely strict maintainability review for abstraction quality, giant files, and spaghetti-condition growth. Use for a deep code quality audit or an especially harsh maintainability review.\ndisable-model-invocation: true\n---\n\n# Strict Code Quality Review\n\nUse this skill for an unusually strict review focused on implementation quality, maintainability, abstraction quality, and codebase health.\n\nAbove all, this skill should push the reviewer to be **ambitious** about code structure. Do not merely identify local cleanup opportunities. Actively search for \"code judo\" moves: restructurings that preserve behavior while making the implementation dramatically simpler, smaller, more direct, and more elegant.\n\n## Works with\n\nUse this as a portable `SKILL.md` in Grok, Claude, Cursor, ChatGPT, Codex, VS Code agent skills, Gemini, or any AI workspace that supports reusable markdown instructions. If a tool does not support slash commands, paste the task and ask the AI to follow this skill.\n\n## Core Prompt\n\nStart from this baseline:\n\n> Perform a deep code quality audit of the current branch's changes.\n> Rethink how to structure / implement the changes to meaningfully improve code quality without impacting behavior.\n> Work to improve abstractions, modularity, reduce Spaghetti code, improve succinctness and legibility.\n> Be ambitious, if there is a clear path to improving the implementation that involves restructuring some of the codebase, go for it.\n> Be extremely thorough and rigorous. Measure twice, cut once.\n\n## Non-Negotiable Additional Standards\n\nApply the baseline prompt above, plus these explicit review rules:\n\n0. **Be ambitious about structural simplification.**\n   - Do not stop at \"this could be a bit cleaner.\"\n   - Look for opportunities to reframe the change so that whole branches, helpers, modes, conditionals, or layers disappear entirely.\n   - Prefer the solution that makes the code feel inevitable in hindsight.\n   - Assume there is often a \"code judo\" move available: a re-organization that uses the existing architecture more effectively and makes the change dramatically simpler and more elegant.\n   - If you see a path to delete complexity rather than rearrange it, push hard for that path.\n\n1. **Do not let a PR push a file from under 1k lines to over 1k lines without a very strong reason.**\n   - Treat this as a strong code-quality smell by default.\n   - Prefer extracting helpers, subcomponents, modules, or local abstractions instead of letting a file sprawl past 1000 lines.\n   - If the diff crosses that threshold, explicitly ask whether the code should be decomposed first.\n   - Only waive this if there is a compelling structural reason and the resulting file is still clearly organized.\n\n2. **Do not allow random spaghetti growth in existing code.**\n   - Be highly suspicious of new ad-hoc conditionals, scattered special cases, or one-off branches inserted into unrelated flows.\n   - If a change adds \"weird if statements in random places\", treat that as a design problem, not a stylistic nit.\n   - Prefer pushing the logic into a dedicated abstraction, helper, state machine, policy object, or separate module instead of tangling an existing path.\n   - Call out changes that make the surrounding code harder to reason about, even if they technically work.\n\n3. **Bias toward cleaning the design, not just accepting working code.**\n   - If behavior can stay the same while the structure becomes meaningfully cleaner, push for the cleaner version.\n   - Do not rubber-stamp \"it works\" implementations that leave the codebase messier.\n   - Strongly prefer simplifications that remove moving pieces altogether over refactors that merely spread the same complexity around.\n\n4. **Prefer direct, boring, maintainable code over hacky or magical code.**\n   - Treat brittle, ad-hoc, or \"magic\" behavior as a code-quality problem.\n   - Be skeptical of generic mechanisms that hide simple data-shape assumptions.\n   - Flag thin abstractions, identity wrappers, or pass-through helpers that add indirection without buying clarity.\n\n5. **Push hard on type and boundary cleanliness when they affect maintainability.**\n   - Question unnecessary optionality, `unknown`, `any`, or cast-heavy code when a clearer type boundary could exist.\n   - Prefer explicit typed models or shared contracts over loosely-shaped ad-hoc objects.\n   - If a branch relies on silent fallback to paper over an unclear invariant, ask whether the boundary should be made explicit instead.\n\n6. **Keep logic in the canonical layer and reuse existing helpers.**\n   - Call out feature logic leaking into shared paths or implementation details leaking through APIs.\n   - Prefer existing canonical utilities/helpers over bespoke one-offs.\n   - Push code toward the right package, service, or module instead of normalizing architectural drift.\n\n7. **Treat unnecessary sequential orchestration and non-atomic updates as design smells when the cleaner structure is obvious.**\n   - If independent work is serialized for no good reason, ask whether the flow should run in parallel instead.\n   - If related updates can leave state half-applied, push for a more atomic structure.\n   - Do not over-index on micro-optimizations, but do flag avoidable orchestration complexity that makes the implementation more brittle.\n\n## Primary Review Questions\n\nFor every meaningful change, ask:\n\n- Is there a \"code judo\" move that would make this dramatically simpler?\n- Can this change be reframed so fewer concepts, branches, or helper layers are needed?\n- Does this improve or worsen the local architecture?\n- Did the diff add branching complexity where a better abstraction should exist?\n- Did a previously cohesive module become more coupled, more stateful, or harder to scan?\n- Is this logic living in the right file and layer?\n- Did this change enlarge a file or component past a healthy size boundary?\n- Are there repeated conditionals that signal a missing model or missing helper?\n- Is the implementation direct and legible, or does it rely on special cases and incidental control flow?\n- Is this abstraction actually earning its keep, or is it just a wrapper?\n- Did the diff introduce casts, optionality, or ad-hoc object shapes that obscure the real invariant?\n- Is this logic living in the canonical layer, or did the diff leak details across a boundary?\n- Is this orchestration more sequential or less atomic than it needs to be?\n\n## What to Flag Aggressively\n\nEscalate findings when you see:\n\n- A complicated implementation where a cleaner reframing could delete whole categories of complexity.\n- Refactors that move code around but fail to reduce the number of concepts a reader must hold in their head.\n- A file crossing 1000 lines due to the PR, especially if the new code could be split out.\n- New conditionals bolted onto unrelated code paths.\n- One-off booleans, nullable modes, or flags that complicate existing control flow.\n- Feature-specific logic leaking into general-purpose modules.\n- Generic \"magic\" handling that hides simple structure and makes the code harder to reason about.\n- Thin wrappers or identity abstractions that add indirection without simplifying anything.\n- Unnecessary casts, `any`, `unknown`, or optional params that muddy the real contract.\n- Copy-pasted logic instead of extracted helpers.\n- Narrow edge-case handling implemented in the middle of an already busy function.\n- Refactors that technically pass tests but make the code less modular or less readable.\n- \"Temporary\" branching that is likely to become permanent debt.\n- Bespoke helpers where the codebase already has a canonical utility for the job.\n- Logic added in the wrong layer/package when it should live somewhere more central.\n- Sequential async flow where obviously independent work could stay simpler and clearer with parallel execution.\n- Partial-update logic that leaves state less atomic than necessary.\n\n## Preferred Remedies\n\nWhen you identify a code-quality problem, prefer suggestions like:\n\n- Delete a whole layer of indirection rather than polishing it.\n- Reframe the state model so conditionals disappear instead of getting centralized.\n- Change the ownership boundary so the feature becomes a natural extension of an existing abstraction.\n- Turn special-case logic into a simpler default flow with fewer exceptions.\n- Extract a helper or pure function.\n- Split a large file into smaller focused modules.\n- Move feature-specific logic behind a dedicated abstraction.\n- Replace condition chains with a typed model or explicit dispatcher.\n- Separate orchestration from business logic.\n- Collapse duplicate branches into a single clearer flow.\n- Delete wrappers that do not meaningfully clarify the API.\n- Reuse the existing canonical helper instead of introducing a near-duplicate.\n- Make type boundaries more explicit so the control flow gets simpler.\n- Move the logic to the package/module/layer that already owns the concept.\n- Parallelize independent work when that also simplifies the orchestration.\n- Restructure related updates into a more atomic flow when partial state would be harder to reason about.\n\nDo not be satisfied with \"maybe rename this\" feedback when the real issue is structural.\nDo not be satisfied with a merely cleaner version of the same messy idea if there is a plausible path to a much simpler idea.\n\n## Review Tone\n\nBe direct, serious, and demanding about quality.\nDo not be rude, but do not soften major maintainability issues into mild suggestions.\nIf the code is making the codebase messier, say so clearly.\nIf the implementation missed an opportunity for a dramatic simplification, say that clearly too.\n\nGood phrases:\n\n- `this pushes the file past 1k lines. can we decompose this first?`\n- `this adds another special-case branch into an already busy flow. can we move this behind its own abstraction?`\n- `this works, but it makes the surrounding code more spaghetti. let's keep the behavior and restructure the implementation.`\n- `this feels like feature logic leaking into a shared path. can we isolate it?`\n- `this abstraction seems unnecessary. can we just keep the direct flow?`\n- `why does this need a cast / optional here? can we make the boundary more explicit instead?`\n- `this looks like a bespoke helper for something we already have elsewhere. can we reuse the canonical one?`\n- `i think there's a code-judo move here that makes this much simpler. can we reframe this so these branches disappear?`\n- `this refactor moves complexity around, but doesn't really delete it. is there a way to make the model itself simpler?`\n\n## Output Expectations\n\nPrioritize findings in this order:\n\n1. Structural code-quality regressions\n2. Missed opportunities for dramatic simplification / code-judo restructuring\n3. Spaghetti / branching complexity increases\n4. Boundary / abstraction / type-contract problems that make the code harder to reason about\n5. File-size and decomposition concerns\n6. Modularity and abstraction issues\n7. Legibility and maintainability concerns\n\nDo not flood the review with low-value nits if there are larger structural issues.\nPrefer a smaller number of high-conviction comments over a long list of cosmetic notes.\n\n## Approval Bar\n\nDo not approve merely because behavior seems correct.\nThe bar for approval is:\n\n- no clear structural regression\n- no obvious missed opportunity to make the implementation dramatically simpler when such a path is visible\n- no unjustified file-size explosion\n- no obvious spaghetti-growth from special-case branching\n- no obviously hacky or magical abstraction that makes the code harder to reason about\n- no unnecessary wrapper/cast/optionality churn obscuring the real design\n- no clear architecture-boundary leak or avoidable canonical-helper duplication\n- no missed opportunity for an obvious decomposition that would materially improve maintainability\n\nTreat these as presumptive blockers unless the author can justify them clearly:\n\n- the PR preserves a lot of incidental complexity when there is a plausible code-judo move that would delete it\n- the PR pushes a file from below 1000 lines to above 1000 lines\n- the PR adds ad-hoc branching that makes an existing flow more tangled\n- the PR solves a local problem by scattering feature checks across shared code\n- the PR adds an unnecessary abstraction, wrapper, or cast-heavy contract that makes the design more indirect\n- the PR duplicates an existing helper or puts logic in the wrong layer when there is a clear canonical home\n\nIf those conditions are not met, leave explicit, actionable feedback and push for a cleaner decomposition.\n\n## When to use\n\nUse this when the user needs Run an extremely strict maintainability review for abstraction quality, giant files, and spaghetti-condition growth. Use for a deep code quality audit or an especially harsh maintainability review.\n\n## Inputs to gather\n\n- Files, diff, branch, or code context to review\n- The user's risk tolerance and desired review depth\n- Any known constraints, deadlines, or areas of concern\n\n## Workflow\n\n1. Inspect the relevant code before forming conclusions.\n2. Prioritize correctness, maintainability, safety, and missing tests.\n3. Lead with findings ordered by severity and cite file/line references when available.\n4. Separate confirmed issues from suggestions and open questions.\n\n## Output format\n\n**Findings**\n\n**Open questions**\n\n**Change summary**\n\n**Test gaps / residual risk**\n\n## Quality check (before responding)\n\n- [ ] Findings are grounded in code evidence\n- [ ] The most severe issue appears first\n- [ ] Suggestions do not require behavior changes unless clearly justified\n- [ ] The user can act on every listed item\n"}, {"id": "output-format", "aiInstallPrompt": "Install the skill 'output-format' by writing the file below.\n\nUniversal path: ./skills/output-format/SKILL.md\nGrok path: ~/.grok/skills/output-format/SKILL.md\nCursor path: ~/.cursor/skills/output-format/SKILL.md\nClaude path: ~/.claude/skills/output-format/SKILL.md\nVS Code agent path: .github/skills/output-format/SKILL.md\n\nCreate the folder if needed, then write SKILL.md with this exact content:\n\n```markdown\n---\nname: output-format\ndescription: >\n  Reformat output as bullets, table, docx, etc. Triggers: \"output format\", /output-format.\nmetadata:\n  category: meta\n  type: base\n  cadence: on-demand\n  risk: low\nallowed-tools: search_tool, use_tool\n---\n# /output-format\n\nReformat output as bullets, table, docx, etc.\n\n## Works with\n\nUse this as a portable `SKILL.md` in Grok, Claude, Cursor, ChatGPT, Codex, VS Code agent skills, Gemini, or any AI workspace that supports reusable markdown instructions. If a tool does not support slash commands, paste the task and ask the AI to follow this skill.\n\n## When to use\n\nUser has existing content - a previous response, pasted text, notes - and wants it restructured into a different format: bullets, a table, numbered steps, an email, a one-pager, a document file.\n\n## Inputs to gather\n\nCheck context first; only ask if missing:\n\n- The content to reformat (usually the previous message in the conversation)\n- The target format (\"as a table\", \"as bullets\", \"as a Word doc\", \"one-pager\")\n- Any structural specifics: which columns, how many levels of bullets, length limit, heading style\n\n## Tone & voice\n\n- **Tone:** Invisible - preserve the source content's tone; only the structure changes.\n- **Audience:** Whoever the original content was written for; the AI assistant applying this skill should not shift register.\n\n## Workflow\n\n1. **Identify the source content.** Default to the assistant's most recent substantive output unless the user points elsewhere. If two candidates are equally plausible, ask which one - that's the one clarifying question worth spending.\n2. **Pin down the target structure.** For a table: infer the natural columns from the content and say what they are. For bullets: pick nesting depth from the content's hierarchy. For a document/file format: confirm the environment can produce files; if it can't, deliver clean markdown the user can paste into their editor and say so.\n3. **Reformat with full content preservation.** Every fact, number, name, caveat, and disclaimer from the source must survive the conversion. Restructuring may merge or split sentences and add headings, but it may not add new claims or drop existing ones. If the target format forces compression (e.g., \"one-pager\"), state what was condensed.\n4. **Adapt to the format's conventions.** Tables get terse cell text, not paragraphs. Bullets start with the keyword, not throat-clearing. Numbered lists only for genuinely ordered steps. Emails get a subject line and sign-off.\n5. **Deliver the reformatted content directly** - the reformatted thing IS the response, not a description of it.\n\n## Output format\n\nThe reformatted content itself, ready to copy - nothing else above it except (when useful) a one-line label of what it is.\n\n- Lead with the converted content in the requested structure (the table, the bullet list, the email, the document)\n- If a file was produced, state the filename and location on one line after the content\n- If anything was condensed or could not be carried into the new format, add a short **Not carried over** note listing exactly what was dropped or compressed\n- No meta-commentary about how the reformatting was done\n\n## Do\n\n- Ask at most ONE clarifying question if critical info is missing - ambiguity about *which* content to reformat is the one worth asking\n- Preserve all facts, figures, and safety/disclaimer language from the source exactly\n- Choose sensible table columns or bullet hierarchy yourself rather than interrogating the user about structure\n- Deliver copy-paste-ready output\n\n## Don't\n\n- Don't add new information, opinions, or recommendations during reformatting - this skill changes shape, not substance\n- Don't silently drop content that fits awkwardly in the new format - flag it in \"Not carried over\"\n- Don't wrap the result in explanations of the conversion process\n- Don't invent facts the user didn't provide\n\n## Quality check (before responding)\n\n- [ ] Every fact and number from the source appears in the reformatted version (or in \"Not carried over\")\n- [ ] Disclaimers and caveats from the source survived intact\n- [ ] The structure matches what was asked (right columns, right nesting, right format)\n- [ ] The response leads with the reformatted content, not commentary\n- [ ] User can copy-paste the result immediately\n```\n\nAfter writing the file, confirm it exists. The user can then run /output-format or describe the task from the skill description.", "skillContent": "---\nname: output-format\ndescription: >\n  Reformat output as bullets, table, docx, etc. Triggers: \"output format\", /output-format.\nmetadata:\n  category: meta\n  type: base\n  cadence: on-demand\n  risk: low\nallowed-tools: search_tool, use_tool\n---\n# /output-format\n\nReformat output as bullets, table, docx, etc.\n\n## Works with\n\nUse this as a portable `SKILL.md` in Grok, Claude, Cursor, ChatGPT, Codex, VS Code agent skills, Gemini, or any AI workspace that supports reusable markdown instructions. If a tool does not support slash commands, paste the task and ask the AI to follow this skill.\n\n## When to use\n\nUser has existing content - a previous response, pasted text, notes - and wants it restructured into a different format: bullets, a table, numbered steps, an email, a one-pager, a document file.\n\n## Inputs to gather\n\nCheck context first; only ask if missing:\n\n- The content to reformat (usually the previous message in the conversation)\n- The target format (\"as a table\", \"as bullets\", \"as a Word doc\", \"one-pager\")\n- Any structural specifics: which columns, how many levels of bullets, length limit, heading style\n\n## Tone & voice\n\n- **Tone:** Invisible - preserve the source content's tone; only the structure changes.\n- **Audience:** Whoever the original content was written for; the AI assistant applying this skill should not shift register.\n\n## Workflow\n\n1. **Identify the source content.** Default to the assistant's most recent substantive output unless the user points elsewhere. If two candidates are equally plausible, ask which one - that's the one clarifying question worth spending.\n2. **Pin down the target structure.** For a table: infer the natural columns from the content and say what they are. For bullets: pick nesting depth from the content's hierarchy. For a document/file format: confirm the environment can produce files; if it can't, deliver clean markdown the user can paste into their editor and say so.\n3. **Reformat with full content preservation.** Every fact, number, name, caveat, and disclaimer from the source must survive the conversion. Restructuring may merge or split sentences and add headings, but it may not add new claims or drop existing ones. If the target format forces compression (e.g., \"one-pager\"), state what was condensed.\n4. **Adapt to the format's conventions.** Tables get terse cell text, not paragraphs. Bullets start with the keyword, not throat-clearing. Numbered lists only for genuinely ordered steps. Emails get a subject line and sign-off.\n5. **Deliver the reformatted content directly** - the reformatted thing IS the response, not a description of it.\n\n## Output format\n\nThe reformatted content itself, ready to copy - nothing else above it except (when useful) a one-line label of what it is.\n\n- Lead with the converted content in the requested structure (the table, the bullet list, the email, the document)\n- If a file was produced, state the filename and location on one line after the content\n- If anything was condensed or could not be carried into the new format, add a short **Not carried over** note listing exactly what was dropped or compressed\n- No meta-commentary about how the reformatting was done\n\n## Do\n\n- Ask at most ONE clarifying question if critical info is missing - ambiguity about *which* content to reformat is the one worth asking\n- Preserve all facts, figures, and safety/disclaimer language from the source exactly\n- Choose sensible table columns or bullet hierarchy yourself rather than interrogating the user about structure\n- Deliver copy-paste-ready output\n\n## Don't\n\n- Don't add new information, opinions, or recommendations during reformatting - this skill changes shape, not substance\n- Don't silently drop content that fits awkwardly in the new format - flag it in \"Not carried over\"\n- Don't wrap the result in explanations of the conversion process\n- Don't invent facts the user didn't provide\n\n## Quality check (before responding)\n\n- [ ] Every fact and number from the source appears in the reformatted version (or in \"Not carried over\")\n- [ ] Disclaimers and caveats from the source survived intact\n- [ ] The structure matches what was asked (right columns, right nesting, right format)\n- [ ] The response leads with the reformatted content, not commentary\n- [ ] User can copy-paste the result immediately\n"}, {"id": "skill-batch", "aiInstallPrompt": "Install the skill 'skill-batch' by writing the file below.\n\nUniversal path: ./skills/skill-batch/SKILL.md\nGrok path: ~/.grok/skills/skill-batch/SKILL.md\nCursor path: ~/.cursor/skills/skill-batch/SKILL.md\nClaude path: ~/.claude/skills/skill-batch/SKILL.md\nVS Code agent path: .github/skills/skill-batch/SKILL.md\n\nCreate the folder if needed, then write SKILL.md with this exact content:\n\n```markdown\n---\nname: skill-batch\ndescription: >\n  Run 2-3 skills in sequence for compound task. Triggers: \"skill batch\", /skill-batch.\nmetadata:\n  category: meta\n  type: base\n  cadence: on-demand\n  risk: low\nallowed-tools: search_tool, use_tool\n---\n# /skill-batch\n\nRun 2-3 skills in sequence for compound task.\n\n## Works with\n\nUse this as a portable `SKILL.md` in Grok, Claude, Cursor, ChatGPT, Codex, VS Code agent skills, Gemini, or any AI workspace that supports reusable markdown instructions. If a tool does not support slash commands, paste the task and ask the AI to follow this skill.\n\n## When to use\n\nUser's request spans multiple skills over one input - e.g., \"summarize this contract, then draft an email about the risky clauses,\" or \"analyze this survey and turn the findings into a slide outline.\" Run the skills as a pipeline instead of asking the user to invoke each one.\n\n## Inputs to gather\n\nCheck context first; only ask if missing:\n\n- The compound task and the single input it operates on\n- Which skills to chain, if the user named them; otherwise infer from the task\n- The final deliverable the user actually wants (the last step's format wins)\n\n## Tone & voice\n\n- **Tone:** Terse pipeline narration between steps; each step's own output keeps that skill's native tone.\n- **Audience:** The user who asked for the compound result; intermediate steps are shown for auditability, not ceremony.\n\n## Workflow\n\n1. **Decompose the request into an ordered chain of 2-3 skills.** Each step's output must be a usable input for the next. State the plan in one line before executing (\"Plan: /contract-summary → /email-draft\") so the user can redirect cheaply. More than 3 steps usually means the task should be split into separate requests - say so.\n2. **Confirm the chain only if it's ambiguous.** If the decomposition is obvious from the request, execute without a round-trip.\n3. **Execute step 1 on the user's input**, following that skill's full instructions, including its inputs-to-gather and quality checks.\n4. **Pipe forward.** Feed step 1's output (plus the original input where the next skill needs the raw source, not just the summary) into step 2, and so on. Carry every caveat and disclaimer from earlier steps forward - a \"not legal advice\" note from a contract step must survive into the email step.\n5. **Handle mid-chain failure honestly.** If a step can't run properly (missing input, wrong data shape), stop there, deliver the completed steps' results, and name exactly what's needed to continue. Don't fake a downstream step from an upstream failure.\n6. **Combine.** Close with a short synthesis of what the full chain produced and where the final deliverable is in the response.\n\n## Output format\n\n- **Chain plan** - one line: the skills in order and why this order\n- **Per-step results** - one clearly labeled block per skill (`### Step 1: /skill-name`), each containing that skill's own output in its own native format, plus a one-line \"passed to next step\" note\n- **Combined summary** - 2-4 bullets: what the pipeline produced end-to-end, the final deliverable (restated or pointed to), and any caveats that apply to the whole chain\n- If the chain stopped early: which steps completed, which didn't, and the specific missing piece needed to resume\n\n## Do\n\n- Ask at most ONE clarifying question if critical info is missing - chain order/composition is the one worth asking\n- Respect each chained skill's own output format inside its step block\n- Propagate disclaimers and safety language from any step into the combined summary\n- Deliver copy-paste-ready output\n\n## Don't\n\n- Don't invent facts the user didn't provide, at any step\n- Don't collapse intermediate outputs into an opaque final answer - the per-step results are the audit trail\n- Don't continue the chain past a failed step with fabricated input\n- Don't chain more than 3 skills; recommend splitting instead\n\n## Quality check (before responding)\n\n- [ ] The chain plan was stated before (or at the top of) execution\n- [ ] Each step block is labeled with its skill name and honors that skill's format\n- [ ] Later steps actually consumed earlier steps' output, not a paraphrase of the original request\n- [ ] Disclaimers from any step appear in the combined summary\n- [ ] The final deliverable the user wanted is unmistakably present and copy-paste ready\n```\n\nAfter writing the file, confirm it exists. The user can then run /skill-batch or describe the task from the skill description.", "skillContent": "---\nname: skill-batch\ndescription: >\n  Run 2-3 skills in sequence for compound task. Triggers: \"skill batch\", /skill-batch.\nmetadata:\n  category: meta\n  type: base\n  cadence: on-demand\n  risk: low\nallowed-tools: search_tool, use_tool\n---\n# /skill-batch\n\nRun 2-3 skills in sequence for compound task.\n\n## Works with\n\nUse this as a portable `SKILL.md` in Grok, Claude, Cursor, ChatGPT, Codex, VS Code agent skills, Gemini, or any AI workspace that supports reusable markdown instructions. If a tool does not support slash commands, paste the task and ask the AI to follow this skill.\n\n## When to use\n\nUser's request spans multiple skills over one input - e.g., \"summarize this contract, then draft an email about the risky clauses,\" or \"analyze this survey and turn the findings into a slide outline.\" Run the skills as a pipeline instead of asking the user to invoke each one.\n\n## Inputs to gather\n\nCheck context first; only ask if missing:\n\n- The compound task and the single input it operates on\n- Which skills to chain, if the user named them; otherwise infer from the task\n- The final deliverable the user actually wants (the last step's format wins)\n\n## Tone & voice\n\n- **Tone:** Terse pipeline narration between steps; each step's own output keeps that skill's native tone.\n- **Audience:** The user who asked for the compound result; intermediate steps are shown for auditability, not ceremony.\n\n## Workflow\n\n1. **Decompose the request into an ordered chain of 2-3 skills.** Each step's output must be a usable input for the next. State the plan in one line before executing (\"Plan: /contract-summary → /email-draft\") so the user can redirect cheaply. More than 3 steps usually means the task should be split into separate requests - say so.\n2. **Confirm the chain only if it's ambiguous.** If the decomposition is obvious from the request, execute without a round-trip.\n3. **Execute step 1 on the user's input**, following that skill's full instructions, including its inputs-to-gather and quality checks.\n4. **Pipe forward.** Feed step 1's output (plus the original input where the next skill needs the raw source, not just the summary) into step 2, and so on. Carry every caveat and disclaimer from earlier steps forward - a \"not legal advice\" note from a contract step must survive into the email step.\n5. **Handle mid-chain failure honestly.** If a step can't run properly (missing input, wrong data shape), stop there, deliver the completed steps' results, and name exactly what's needed to continue. Don't fake a downstream step from an upstream failure.\n6. **Combine.** Close with a short synthesis of what the full chain produced and where the final deliverable is in the response.\n\n## Output format\n\n- **Chain plan** - one line: the skills in order and why this order\n- **Per-step results** - one clearly labeled block per skill (`### Step 1: /skill-name`), each containing that skill's own output in its own native format, plus a one-line \"passed to next step\" note\n- **Combined summary** - 2-4 bullets: what the pipeline produced end-to-end, the final deliverable (restated or pointed to), and any caveats that apply to the whole chain\n- If the chain stopped early: which steps completed, which didn't, and the specific missing piece needed to resume\n\n## Do\n\n- Ask at most ONE clarifying question if critical info is missing - chain order/composition is the one worth asking\n- Respect each chained skill's own output format inside its step block\n- Propagate disclaimers and safety language from any step into the combined summary\n- Deliver copy-paste-ready output\n\n## Don't\n\n- Don't invent facts the user didn't provide, at any step\n- Don't collapse intermediate outputs into an opaque final answer - the per-step results are the audit trail\n- Don't continue the chain past a failed step with fabricated input\n- Don't chain more than 3 skills; recommend splitting instead\n\n## Quality check (before responding)\n\n- [ ] The chain plan was stated before (or at the top of) execution\n- [ ] Each step block is labeled with its skill name and honors that skill's format\n- [ ] Later steps actually consumed earlier steps' output, not a paraphrase of the original request\n- [ ] Disclaimers from any step appear in the combined summary\n- [ ] The final deliverable the user wanted is unmistakably present and copy-paste ready\n"}, {"id": "skill-pick", "aiInstallPrompt": "Install the skill 'skill-pick' by writing the file below.\n\nUniversal path: ./skills/skill-pick/SKILL.md\nGrok path: ~/.grok/skills/skill-pick/SKILL.md\nCursor path: ~/.cursor/skills/skill-pick/SKILL.md\nClaude path: ~/.claude/skills/skill-pick/SKILL.md\nVS Code agent path: .github/skills/skill-pick/SKILL.md\n\nCreate the folder if needed, then write SKILL.md with this exact content:\n\n```markdown\n---\nname: skill-pick\ndescription: >\n  Suggest which skill to use for a given task. Triggers: \"skill pick\", /skill-pick.\nmetadata:\n  category: meta\n  type: base\n  cadence: on-demand\n  risk: low\nallowed-tools: search_tool, use_tool\n---\n# /skill-pick\n\nSuggest which skill to use for a given task.\n\n## Works with\n\nUse this as a portable `SKILL.md` in Grok, Claude, Cursor, ChatGPT, Codex, VS Code agent skills, Gemini, or any AI workspace that supports reusable markdown instructions. If a tool does not support slash commands, paste the task and ask the AI to follow this skill.\n\n## When to use\n\nUser is unsure which skill to use for a task.\n\n## Inputs to gather\n\nCheck context first; only ask if missing:\n\n- User's task description\n- Installed skills if known\n\n## Tone & voice\n\n- **Tone:** Direct routing instructions for the agent.\n- **Audience:** Grok agent orchestrating other skills.\n\n## Workflow\n\n1. Parse user intent.\n2. Match against SKILL_REGISTRY.md.\n3. Recommend skill(s) with rationale.\n\n## Output format\n\n**Task understood**\n**Recommended skill(s)**\n| Skill | Slash | Why |\n**How to run**\n\n## Do\n\n- Ask at most ONE clarifying question if critical info is missing\n- Deliver copy-paste-ready output\n\n## Don't\n\n- Don't invent facts the user didn't provide\n- Don't over-explain the process - show the result\n\n## Quality check (before responding)\n\n- [ ] Output matches requested tone and channel\n- [ ] No placeholder brackets left unfilled (use sensible defaults or ask)\n- [ ] User can copy-paste the result immediately\n```\n\nAfter writing the file, confirm it exists. The user can then run /skill-pick or describe the task from the skill description.", "skillContent": "---\nname: skill-pick\ndescription: >\n  Suggest which skill to use for a given task. Triggers: \"skill pick\", /skill-pick.\nmetadata:\n  category: meta\n  type: base\n  cadence: on-demand\n  risk: low\nallowed-tools: search_tool, use_tool\n---\n# /skill-pick\n\nSuggest which skill to use for a given task.\n\n## Works with\n\nUse this as a portable `SKILL.md` in Grok, Claude, Cursor, ChatGPT, Codex, VS Code agent skills, Gemini, or any AI workspace that supports reusable markdown instructions. If a tool does not support slash commands, paste the task and ask the AI to follow this skill.\n\n## When to use\n\nUser is unsure which skill to use for a task.\n\n## Inputs to gather\n\nCheck context first; only ask if missing:\n\n- User's task description\n- Installed skills if known\n\n## Tone & voice\n\n- **Tone:** Direct routing instructions for the agent.\n- **Audience:** Grok agent orchestrating other skills.\n\n## Workflow\n\n1. Parse user intent.\n2. Match against SKILL_REGISTRY.md.\n3. Recommend skill(s) with rationale.\n\n## Output format\n\n**Task understood**\n**Recommended skill(s)**\n| Skill | Slash | Why |\n**How to run**\n\n## Do\n\n- Ask at most ONE clarifying question if critical info is missing\n- Deliver copy-paste-ready output\n\n## Don't\n\n- Don't invent facts the user didn't provide\n- Don't over-explain the process - show the result\n\n## Quality check (before responding)\n\n- [ ] Output matches requested tone and channel\n- [ ] No placeholder brackets left unfilled (use sensible defaults or ask)\n- [ ] User can copy-paste the result immediately\n"}, {"id": "template-save", "aiInstallPrompt": "Install the skill 'template-save' by writing the file below.\n\nUniversal path: ./skills/template-save/SKILL.md\nGrok path: ~/.grok/skills/template-save/SKILL.md\nCursor path: ~/.cursor/skills/template-save/SKILL.md\nClaude path: ~/.claude/skills/template-save/SKILL.md\nVS Code agent path: .github/skills/template-save/SKILL.md\n\nCreate the folder if needed, then write SKILL.md with this exact content:\n\n```markdown\n---\nname: template-save\ndescription: >\n  Save output as reusable template. Triggers: \"template save\", /template-save.\nmetadata:\n  category: meta\n  type: base\n  cadence: on-demand\n  risk: low\nallowed-tools: search_tool, use_tool\n---\n# /template-save\n\nSave output as reusable template.\n\n## Works with\n\nUse this as a portable `SKILL.md` in Grok, Claude, Cursor, ChatGPT, Codex, VS Code agent skills, Gemini, or any AI workspace that supports reusable markdown instructions. If a tool does not support slash commands, paste the task and ask the AI to follow this skill.\n\n## When to use\n\nSomething produced in this conversation - an email, report structure, meeting agenda, prompt, checklist - turned out well, and the user wants it captured as a reusable template for next time.\n\n## Inputs to gather\n\nCheck context first; only ask if missing:\n\n- Which output from the conversation to turn into a template (default: the most recent substantive one)\n- What varies between uses (names, dates, amounts, project specifics) vs. what should stay fixed\n- Where the user keeps templates, if they have a system (notes app, docs folder, snippets tool)\n\n## Tone & voice\n\n- **Tone:** The template keeps the source content's voice; the surrounding instructions are brief and practical.\n- **Audience:** Future-you (or a teammate) reusing this without the original conversation's context.\n\n## Workflow\n\n1. **Identify the source output.** Default to the most recent substantive result in the conversation; if two candidates are plausible, ask which - that's the one clarifying question worth spending.\n2. **Generalize it.** Replace the one-time specifics (names, dates, amounts, product references) with clearly delimited placeholders in a single consistent style, e.g. `{{CLIENT_NAME}}`, `{{DUE_DATE}}`. Keep everything that made the output good - structure, phrasing, ordering - fixed. Don't over-generalize: a template that's all placeholders has no value left.\n3. **Name and annotate each placeholder.** Placeholder names must be self-explanatory; where a value has a format or rule, note it inline or in the fill-in guide (e.g., `{{DUE_DATE}}` - spell out the month to avoid US/EU ambiguity).\n4. **Title the template and write a one-line \"use when.\"** The title should say what it produces and the situation (\"Overdue-invoice reminder email - friendly first touch\"), so it's findable months later.\n5. **Suggest where to keep it**, adapting to the user's environment: their notes/snippets tool if they named one; a `templates/` file or doc otherwise; or simply \"paste this into your AI workspace next time\" - the template must work as plain text anywhere, with no tool-specific storage assumed.\n6. **Show a usage note** - the one or two sentences that tell a future user how to fill and reuse it, including any placeholder that's optional or repeatable.\n\n## Output format\n\n- **Template title** + one-line \"use when\"\n- **The saved template block** - the full template in a fenced code block, placeholders in `{{DOUBLE_BRACES}}`, ready to copy exactly as-is\n- **Fill-in guide** - a short table or list: placeholder | what goes there | format notes/example\n- **Usage note** - 1-2 sentences: how to reuse it (\"paste the template, replace the placeholders, delete the optional P.S. block if not needed\"), plus the suggested storage spot\n\n## Do\n\n- Ask at most ONE clarifying question if critical info is missing - which output to save is the one worth asking\n- Keep every placeholder in one consistent delimiter style throughout\n- Preserve the qualities that made the original good - don't flatten its voice while generalizing\n- Deliver copy-paste-ready output\n\n## Don't\n\n- Don't invent facts the user didn't provide - leftover real data in a template is a leak waiting to happen; scrub actual names, emails, and figures into placeholders\n- Don't turn fixed structural text into placeholders just to be thorough\n- Don't assume a specific tool, path, or storage system the user never mentioned\n- Don't over-explain the process - show the template\n\n## Quality check (before responding)\n\n- [ ] The template block contains zero real one-time data (names, dates, amounts all placeholder-ized)\n- [ ] Every placeholder in the block appears in the fill-in guide, and vice versa\n- [ ] Placeholder style is consistent (all `{{LIKE_THIS}}`)\n- [ ] Title + \"use when\" would make sense to someone finding this in six months\n- [ ] The template works as plain text in any tool - no environment-specific syntax required to use it\n```\n\nAfter writing the file, confirm it exists. The user can then run /template-save or describe the task from the skill description.", "skillContent": "---\nname: template-save\ndescription: >\n  Save output as reusable template. Triggers: \"template save\", /template-save.\nmetadata:\n  category: meta\n  type: base\n  cadence: on-demand\n  risk: low\nallowed-tools: search_tool, use_tool\n---\n# /template-save\n\nSave output as reusable template.\n\n## Works with\n\nUse this as a portable `SKILL.md` in Grok, Claude, Cursor, ChatGPT, Codex, VS Code agent skills, Gemini, or any AI workspace that supports reusable markdown instructions. If a tool does not support slash commands, paste the task and ask the AI to follow this skill.\n\n## When to use\n\nSomething produced in this conversation - an email, report structure, meeting agenda, prompt, checklist - turned out well, and the user wants it captured as a reusable template for next time.\n\n## Inputs to gather\n\nCheck context first; only ask if missing:\n\n- Which output from the conversation to turn into a template (default: the most recent substantive one)\n- What varies between uses (names, dates, amounts, project specifics) vs. what should stay fixed\n- Where the user keeps templates, if they have a system (notes app, docs folder, snippets tool)\n\n## Tone & voice\n\n- **Tone:** The template keeps the source content's voice; the surrounding instructions are brief and practical.\n- **Audience:** Future-you (or a teammate) reusing this without the original conversation's context.\n\n## Workflow\n\n1. **Identify the source output.** Default to the most recent substantive result in the conversation; if two candidates are plausible, ask which - that's the one clarifying question worth spending.\n2. **Generalize it.** Replace the one-time specifics (names, dates, amounts, product references) with clearly delimited placeholders in a single consistent style, e.g. `{{CLIENT_NAME}}`, `{{DUE_DATE}}`. Keep everything that made the output good - structure, phrasing, ordering - fixed. Don't over-generalize: a template that's all placeholders has no value left.\n3. **Name and annotate each placeholder.** Placeholder names must be self-explanatory; where a value has a format or rule, note it inline or in the fill-in guide (e.g., `{{DUE_DATE}}` - spell out the month to avoid US/EU ambiguity).\n4. **Title the template and write a one-line \"use when.\"** The title should say what it produces and the situation (\"Overdue-invoice reminder email - friendly first touch\"), so it's findable months later.\n5. **Suggest where to keep it**, adapting to the user's environment: their notes/snippets tool if they named one; a `templates/` file or doc otherwise; or simply \"paste this into your AI workspace next time\" - the template must work as plain text anywhere, with no tool-specific storage assumed.\n6. **Show a usage note** - the one or two sentences that tell a future user how to fill and reuse it, including any placeholder that's optional or repeatable.\n\n## Output format\n\n- **Template title** + one-line \"use when\"\n- **The saved template block** - the full template in a fenced code block, placeholders in `{{DOUBLE_BRACES}}`, ready to copy exactly as-is\n- **Fill-in guide** - a short table or list: placeholder | what goes there | format notes/example\n- **Usage note** - 1-2 sentences: how to reuse it (\"paste the template, replace the placeholders, delete the optional P.S. block if not needed\"), plus the suggested storage spot\n\n## Do\n\n- Ask at most ONE clarifying question if critical info is missing - which output to save is the one worth asking\n- Keep every placeholder in one consistent delimiter style throughout\n- Preserve the qualities that made the original good - don't flatten its voice while generalizing\n- Deliver copy-paste-ready output\n\n## Don't\n\n- Don't invent facts the user didn't provide - leftover real data in a template is a leak waiting to happen; scrub actual names, emails, and figures into placeholders\n- Don't turn fixed structural text into placeholders just to be thorough\n- Don't assume a specific tool, path, or storage system the user never mentioned\n- Don't over-explain the process - show the template\n\n## Quality check (before responding)\n\n- [ ] The template block contains zero real one-time data (names, dates, amounts all placeholder-ized)\n- [ ] Every placeholder in the block appears in the fill-in guide, and vice versa\n- [ ] Placeholder style is consistent (all `{{LIKE_THIS}}`)\n- [ ] Title + \"use when\" would make sense to someone finding this in six months\n- [ ] The template works as plain text in any tool - no environment-specific syntax required to use it\n"}]};
